sect2.para:
For the past several decades, many mental health professionals have approached diagnosis using some iteration of the Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders (DSM). The current iteration of the DSM is the DSM-5-Text Revision (American Psychiatric Association, 
            2022
         ), which is widely used in the United States and Australia. These diagnoses largely map onto the International Statistical Classification of Diseases and Related Health Problems (11th edition) (World Health Organization, 
            2018
         )—a diagnostic framework that much of the rest of the world uses. These diagnostic systems use a categorical-polythetic classification approach to mental disorder classification. This approach assumes that psychopathology can be classified, like medical diseases, into distinct categories—where meeting a diagnostic threshold includes having a sufficient number and range of symptoms. A benefit to such a system for diagnosis is that it capitalizes on reliability. Indeed, when using structured clinical interview, reliability coefficients tend to be high relative to unstructured means (Osorio et al., 
            2019
         ). Thus, this chapter focuses on a more structured approach to diagnosis to promote consistency in diagnostic clinical interviewing.

Lastly, the AMPD is recognized and included in Sect. III (Emerging Models and Measures) of the DSM-5-TR. AMPD is a dimensional model that is used to diagnose personality disorders. There is a self-report method to assess personality impairment severity (Morey,
            2017
         ) though it is not yet practical to use in clinical practice due to lack of normative data and clear guidelines as to how to interpret high and low scale scores. However, a structured clinical interview has been developed and validated to assess dimensional personality traits (First et al., 2017) and will be discussed below.
